## pass@k vs pass^k — two ways to score multi-sample agents
direction: down

setup: {
  label: "Setup: agent is run K times\non the same task. Each run\neither succeeds (1) or fails (0)."
  shape: rectangle
  style.fill: "#dbeafe"
  style.stroke: "#2563eb"
  body: {label: "Example: K=4 runs on task X\nRun 1: ✓  Run 2: ✗  Run 3: ✓  Run 4: ✗"; shape: text}
}

passk: {
  label: "pass@k\n(any one succeeded)"
  shape: rectangle
  style.fill: "#dcfce7"
  style.stroke: "#16a34a"
  body: {label: "Score: 1 if any run succeeded, else 0\nIn the example: 1 (runs 1 & 3 passed)\n\nMeans: 'with K attempts and an oracle\npicking the best, can you solve it?'"; shape: text}
  use: {label: "Use when:\n• You will retry / cherry-pick\n• Eval measures CAPABILITY\n('can the model solve it at all?')"; shape: text; style.font-color: "#16a34a"}
}

passpowerk: {
  label: "pass^k\n(ALL runs succeeded)"
  shape: rectangle
  style.fill: "#fde68a"
  style.stroke: "#d97706"
  body: {label: "Score: 1 only if every run succeeded\nIn the example: 0 (runs 2 & 4 failed)\n\nMeans: 'can you do this reliably,\nN times in a row, every time?'"; shape: text}
  use: {label: "Use when:\n• Production deployment\n• No retry / no oracle\n• Eval measures RELIABILITY\n('will this work in real users' hands?')"; shape: text; style.font-color: "#d97706"}
}

verdict: {
  shape: text
  label: "Anthropic (Jan 2026): for production agents,\npass^k is the meaningful metric.\npass@k inflates capability numbers and\nhides reliability gaps in user-facing systems."
  style.italic: true
  style.bold: true
  style.font-color: "#7c3aed"
}

setup -> passk
setup -> passpowerk
passk -> verdict
passpowerk -> verdict
